Session 1 — Foundations: sync vs async & the event loop
Why does asyncio exist?
Python is single-threaded. When your code does something slow — like reading a file, making an HTTP call, or waiting for a database — it blocks the entire thread. Nothing else can run.
python# BLOCKING — the thread sits idle during each sleep
import time

def fetch_data(name, delay):
    print(f"Fetching {name}...")
    time.sleep(delay)           # thread is frozen here
    print(f"Done: {name}")

start = time.time()
fetch_data("users", 2)
fetch_data("orders", 3)
fetch_data("products", 1)
print(f"Total: {time.time() - start:.1f}s")   # 6.0s — purely sequential
asyncio lets you suspend a function while it waits, and run other code in the meantime — all in one thread.

The three pillars you must understand first
Coroutine  →  a function defined with async def that can be paused
Awaitable  →  anything you can use await on (coroutine, Task, Future)
Event Loop →  the engine that schedules and runs all coroutines

Example 1 — Your first coroutine
pythonimport asyncio

async def greet(name):          # async def makes this a coroutine function
    print(f"Hello, {name}!")
    await asyncio.sleep(1)      # suspend HERE — other code can run
    print(f"Bye, {name}!")

asyncio.run(greet("Alice"))     # asyncio.run() creates the event loop and runs it
Key insight: calling greet("Alice") does NOT run the function. It returns a coroutine object. Only asyncio.run() (or await) actually executes it.
pythoncoro = greet("Alice")
print(type(coro))   # <class 'coroutine'> — nothing has run yet!
asyncio.run(coro)   # NOW it runs

Example 2 — The power of async: tasks running concurrently
pythonimport asyncio
import time

async def fetch_data(name, delay):
    print(f"  → Starting: {name}")
    await asyncio.sleep(delay)      # gives up control to the event loop
    print(f"  ✓ Done:     {name}")
    return f"data_from_{name}"

async def main():
    start = time.time()

    # Run all three CONCURRENTLY — total ≈ 3s (longest one), not 6s
    results = await asyncio.gather(
        fetch_data("users",    2),
        fetch_data("orders",   3),
        fetch_data("products", 1),
    )

    print(f"\nResults: {results}")
    print(f"Total:   {time.time() - start:.1f}s")   # ≈ 3.0s

asyncio.run(main())
